# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] The **1950 College World Series** was the fourth NCAA-sanctioned baseball tournament that determined a national champion.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] The tournament was held as the conclusion of the 1950 NCAA baseball season and was played at Johnny Rosenblatt Stadium in Omaha, Nebraska from June 15 to June 23.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] It was the first College World Series to be held at the stadium, which hosted the event through 2010.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] The tournament's champion was the Texas Longhorns, coached by Bibb Falk.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] The Most Outstanding Player was Ray VanCleef of Rutgers.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] The championship was the second consecutive for the Longhorns.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] The tournament consisted of no preliminary round of play, as teams were selected directly into the College World Series.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] From 1947 to 1949, there likewise was no preliminary round, as the teams were chosen based on committee selections, conference champions, and district playoffs.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1950-college-world-series] From 1954 to the present, teams compete in the NCAA Division I baseball tournament preliminary round(s), to determine the eight teams that play in the College World Series.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The **1966 NCAA University Division baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 1966 NCAA University Division baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its twentieth year.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] Eight regional districts sent representatives to the College World Series with preliminary rounds within each district serving to determine each representative.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] These events would later become known as regionals.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] Each district had its own format for selecting teams, resulting in 29 teams participating in the tournament at the conclusion of their regular season, and in some cases, after a conference tournament.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The twentieth tournament's champion was Ohio State, coached by Marty Karow.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The Most Outstanding Player was Steve Arlin of Ohio State.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The opening rounds of the tournament were played across eight district sites across the country, each consisting of between two and four teams.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The winners of each District advanced to the College World Series.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] Preliminary rounds at Greeley, CO and Laramie, WY.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1966-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The following players were members of the All-Tournament Team.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1968-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The **1968 NCAA University Division baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 1968 NCAA University Division baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1968-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its twenty-second year.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1968-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] Each district had its own format for selecting teams, resulting in 27 teams participating in the tournament at the conclusion of their regular season, and in some cases, after a conference tournament.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1968-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The twenty-second tournament's champion was the Southern California, coached by Rod Dedeaux.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1968-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The Most Outstanding Player was Bill Seinsoth of the Southern California.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1970-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The **1970 NCAA University Division baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 1970 NCAA University Division baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1970-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its twenty-fourth year.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1970-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] Each district had its own format for selecting teams, resulting in 26 teams participating in the tournament at the conclusion of their regular season, and in some cases, after a conference tournament.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1970-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The twenty-fourth tournament's champion was the Southern California, coached by Rod Dedeaux.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1970-ncaa-university-division-baseball-tournament] The Most Outstanding Player was Gene Ammann of Florida State.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The **1986 NCAA Division I baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 1986 NCAA Division I baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its fortieth year.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Eight regional competitions were held to determine the participants in the final event.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Four regions held a four team, double-elimination tournament while the remaining four regions included six teams, resulting in 40 teams participating in the tournament at the conclusion of their regular season, and in some cases, after a conference tournament.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The fortieth tournament's champion was Arizona, coached by Jerry Kindall.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The Most Outstanding Player was Mike Senne of Arizona.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The opening rounds of the tournament were played across eight regional sites across the country, four consisting of four teams and four of six teams.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1986-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The winners of each Regional advanced to the College World Series.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The **1988 NCAA Division I baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 1988 NCAA Division I baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its forty-second year.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Each region was composed of six teams, resulting in 48 teams participating in the tournament at the conclusion of their regular season, and in some cases, after a conference tournament.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The forty-second tournament's champion was Stanford coached by Mark Marquess.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The Most Outstanding Player was Lee Plemel of Stanford.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The opening rounds of the tournament were played across eight regional sites across the country, each consisting of a six-team field.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Each regional tournament is double-elimination, however region brackets are variable depending on the number of teams remaining after each round.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] In 1988, for the first time, the NCAA seeded all six teams in each regional.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] After 38 seasons as a full double-elimination tournament, the format changed for 1988.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Teams were split into two four-team double-elimination brackets, with the winners of each bracket meeting in a one-game championship.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1988-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Of the 15 tournaments in which a single championship game was played, this was the only one where both teams entered the final with a loss.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1990-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The **1990 NCAA Division I baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 1990 NCAA Division I baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1990-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its forty fourth year.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1990-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The forty-fourth tournament's champion was Georgia, coached by Steve Webber.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1990-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The Most Outstanding Player was Mike Rebhan of Georgia.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1990-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Each regional tournament is double-elimination.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/1990-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The following players were members of the College World Series All-Tournament Team.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] The program's first year of competition was 1870.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] For their first 37 seasons, the program competed without a head coach, compiling a record of 102-157-1.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] The 2007 baseball squad tied the school record for victories with 42 and tallied numbers of 63 home runs and 425 RBIs, good enough for second-most in school history.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] The team finished in first place in the Big East in the regular season, and won the 2007 Big East Conference baseball tournament A record high 6 players would be selected in the 2007 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] The home runs record would go on to be broken in the 2010 season.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] Under head coach Joe Litterio, Rutgers Baseball made the transition from the American Athletic Conference to the Big Ten Conference.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] On May 28, 2019, Joe Litterio's contract was not renewed.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] On June 26 2019, Steve Owens was announced as the new head coach of the Rutgers program.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] Rutgers plays at Bainton Field, a 1,500 seat facility located on the campus of Rutgers University in Piscataway, New Jersey.
[src:rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball/rutgers-scarlet-knights-baseball] As of 2020, at least 25 former Scarlet Knights, including Todd Frazier, Eric Young and David DeJesus, have played in Major League Baseball and 72 players have been selected from the school in the Major League Baseball draft.
